Snape was revealed at the end to be a sympathetic character --
ultimately a good person.  Snape died as a result of his efforts to
protect Harry.  We may choose not to accept Snape as a good character at
the end just as we may choose not to accept Darth Vader as a good
character at the end.  But the point of both stories is that good won
out, the presumably evil characters saved the day and after their deaths
they were remembered fondly by the protagonists.  Snape made a mistake
when he believed Voldemort would spare Lily, and he spent the rest of
his life doing what he could to make up for it.  He was Dumbledore's spy
in Voldemort's camp.  He fed some information to Voldemort but withheld
the essentials as Dumbledore directed.  He swore to protect the children
of Hogwarts.  He spied and lied and put himself in mortal danger to keep
Lily Potter's son safe.  He killed Dumbledore as an act of mercy. Harry
and Ginny even named one of their kids after Snape.

Snape's true nature was hinted at throughout the books.  His revelation
as a good character is one of the big &quot;reveals&quot; at the end of a story,
like the revelation in &quot;Great Expectations&quot; that Pip's benefactor was
the criminal we met at the beginning.  We are intended to view Snape as
good.  As I said, we may choose not to, and that's our business, but in
the world of Harry Potter Snape turned out to be a good guy.

