Agreed.

I think &quot;good&quot; is just to simplistic a term for Snape.  He was a
complicated character.  The truth that we learn about him is that he
had actually loved someone once, and very strongly; he felt terrible
remorse when he accidentally got her killed; and he spent the rest of
his life trying to keep her son safe (and to destroy the man who had
murdered her, which, given the circumstances, was more or less the
same thing). We know that in following this chosen course, Snape
willingly took huge risks (so we have to give him &quot;brave&quot;), and paid
the ultimate price at the end - and that his final action provided
Harry with the information he needed to ultimately defeat Voldemort.
On the other hand, we also know that, after Lily's death,  Snape
remained a mean-spirited, cruel person who mistreated and insulted his
students at every opportunity, that he made life miserable for Harry
in particular (despite keeping him physically safe), and that he
maintained a murderous grudge against his old school rivals for over a
decade (and was more than willing to see two of them fed to dementors)
- which are not the attributes of a nice guy.  The man was a definite
shade of gray, and doesn't fit well into either the black or white
category.
